<br>
  Many things can help you out here...<br>
<br>
1. Like someone said before, recast until you get the highest pet possible. At low levels you can still cast yellow pets sometimes. It is COMPLETELY worth the gems. As long as you can do at least half the damage to the creature (damage from damage shields do not count for the pet) you take no exp penalty like you would grouping with someone higher than you <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
2. At low levels ALWAYS hand your pet rusty two handed sword or halbred, or look for a high level mage to summon you a high damage staff (I hand out 9 damage the Staff of Runes all the time). Your pet will hit for a max of twice the listed weapon damage (so with a Staff of Runes or other 9 damage weapon your pet could hit for 18pts max).<br>
<br>
3. Try to get buffs for you pet as much as possible. Even if it is low level buffs (even skin like wood!) since every little bit helps. Also get buffs for yourself (see #4 to find out why) <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  Look for high level Clerics and Druids for some nice hit point buffs. Often they can double, tripple, quadruple your hit point total (and that of your pet) or EVEN more, not to mention regeneration type spells that remove any sort of down time. Shamen and Enchanters can give enough buffs to make it like you have an extra level or two worth of power. God forbid you should get a clarity <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :lol --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/laugh.gif ALT=":lol"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  since at your level you'd never be able to make your mana bar go down <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  And oh my gosh, if you happen to run across a friendly mage (same one that summoned the staff for you) get a damage sheild before you head into combat. Heck, a nice enough damage shield and a few HP buffs and you can forget abuot the pet for a while <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
4. Like also covered before, at this level you will almost HAVE to tank for your pet. They simply do not have the hit points to take a beating. Start off with a couple nukes, back aff as the monster runs at you. Once the pet pulls the MOB off of you nuke nuke nuke til the thing is so mad at you it ignores the pet. You should have the hits to be able to finish it off. Sometimes if you have a good pet with a rusty weapon, the creature may never come after you since the pet is out damaging you <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  Just step up and it'll start beating on you instead.<br>
<br>
Anyway... just hang in there, cause it always goes in cycles for us. The levels right after we get new spells we can own higher level stuff. But right before we get the new stuff even the smallest creme puff creature can give us troubles <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  Same for many spell casters actually <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Take care, and good hunting <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p><b>Ommundan Rii</b><br>
<img src="http://home.cfl.rr.com/exarch/LLRINGS.GIF"><br>
Master of the Hunt<br>
